hlāw</i> ‘hill’. This name was taken Ireland in the 13th and 17th centuries. See also   Laidlaw  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Laidlaw","meanings":["Scottish: Border surname found mainly around Selkirk and the vales of Ettrick and Yarrow; a Scottish development of   Ludlow  ."]},{"name":"Ledlow","meanings":["English, Irish, or Scottish: variant of   Ludlow   or   Laidlaw  ."]},{"name":"Ludlam","meanings":["English: possibly from a misreading of <i>w</i> as <i>m</i> in <i>Ludelawe</i>, a recorded medieval spelling of the placename <i>Ludlow</i> in Shropshire. Compare   Ludlow  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Ludlow was born in 1248, in Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales. She had at least 2 sons with John Reade. She died in 1348, in her hometown, at the age of 100, and was buried in Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales."},"et":{"1248–1348":"1248–1348","1248–Male":"1248–Surnud","1278–1370":"1278–1370","1278–Male":"1278–Surnud","1348":"1348","1248":"1248","1278":"1278","1370":"1370","Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1248–1348":"1248–1348","1248–Male":"1248–Kuollut","1278–1370":"1278–1370","1278–Male":"1278–Kuollut","1348":"1348","1248":"1248","1278":"1278","1370":"1370","Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1248–1348":"1248–1348","1248–Male":"1248–Décédé","1278–1370":"1278–1370","1278–Male":"1278–Décédé","1348":"1348","1248":"1248","1278":"1278","1370":"1370","Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Joan Ludlow est née en 1248, à Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Galles. Elle a eu au moins 2 fils avec John Reade. Elle est décédée en 1348, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 100 ans, et a été enterrée à Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Galles."},"de":{"1248–1348":"1248–1348","1248–Male":"1248–Verstorben","1278–1370":"1278–1370","1278–Male":"1278–Verstorben","1348":"1348","1248":"1248","1278":"1278","1370":"1370","Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales","lifeSummary":"Joan Ludlow wurde 1248 in Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales geboren. Sie hatte mit John Reade mindestens 2 Söhne. Sie starb 1348 im Alter von 100 Jahren in ihrem Geburtsort und wurde in Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales begraben."},"ht":{"1248–1348":"1248–1348","1248–Male":"1248–Desede","1278–1370":"1278–1370","1278–Male":"1278–Desede","